<h1>4. 'user' is a political category </h1>

<p>

The next observation is about the category of the user - Currently the user
has no rights. The user can only agree to the terms and conditions to
participate in the online life.
The user is forbidden from being political. Various tactics of aesthetic
mediation, shadow banning, warning, intimidation and denial are used.
Looking at the ‚Äòuser‚Äô from Marx-ian lens - the category of labor, resource,
product and surplus.
The categories collapse and the user foes the labor, is the resource (in terms
of data) and is also the product. The surplus and the wages - both collapse
into the category of profit.
If I ask Zuck, it is leisure and not labor, the resource is the compute power
and yes - the raw material is the human - the user, the voluntary user.
The citizen, the actor, the mask, the historical body, the consumer, the voter,
the influencer, the hacker, the bureaucrat, the pirate and the coder - the
singular in the public, different from singular in the data. How the production
of desire affects positions and perspectives ?
What tools do we as users need to assert our political rights as users ?
What differentiates the phantom publics of Nepal from the sit in publics of
Occupy movement?
What is it that doesn‚Äôt make the user ask for more than the ability to like share
and subscribe?
How is it that the users can identify - isolation, depression, provide new
vocabularies, but not question their positions as users in the isolationist
tech ?
The social media billionaire is an old category - the new category is the ai
billionaire. This points to a future where ai consumes the data produced by
the user and regurgitates it into new configurations of the voice, personae,
body, ‚Äòlinguistic thought‚Äô and even a public. The voice without a body, a body
without a voice, and a body with thought. The scope of influence that we as
individuals have on each other is immense. There is an immense potential in
conversation.
What is the scope of phantom conversations ? A phantom public made real
and real made phantom in the image of each other. This has profound
political consequences that are worth considering.
The recent budget was based on the category of the content creator and
influencer. How do we understand this shift from the reason based society to
innovation based society and not to an influencer society?
In a recent talk given by the Chief of Army Staff, General Upendra Dwivedi,
he spoke about narrative management systems and how victory is in the
mind.
In all of this - the person playing the part of the voter, the citizen, the
immigrant, the consumer, the vigilante, the user, the influencer - are all
dynamically chosen. Part of the beauty and hope is that these masks are
flippable ‚Äî The immigrant becomes the influencer - as with Mamdani. The
citizen influencer becomes a threat to national security - as with Sonam
Wangchuk. RSS member becomes spy becomes hacker becomes solider.
And everyone is skating in the mediatic landscape.
So when the public becomes phantom, the public space has to be exorcised.
It will take an epistemic shift for every one of us to reach a digital ecology that
is public, where we can meet.
The status of the user is as serious as the status of a citizen.
We have migrated from Orkut to Facebook to instagram and now it is a
matter of building consensus about an epistemic shift in what we consider
digital public spaces.
To fellow media artists, technologists and media theorists I would like to say -
We have to seize the means of computation. this is the moment to build the
tools for asserting our rights as users, sitting together and building
frameworks that are computable, that work at the level of neural networks.
We need to break the code and legally challenge the contracts that bind us.
